Introduction

Water scarcity is a major issue in many parts of the world. According to the United Nations, “About two billion people worldwide don’t have access to safe drinking water today (SDG Report 2022), and roughly half of the world’s population is experiencing severe water scarcity for at least part of the year (IPCC). These numbers are expected to increase, exacerbated by climate change and population growth (WMO).”

In this problem set, we will investigate water usage estimates by crop in the United States. The .csv for this data set comes from here (by checking Select All and clicking Get Custom Zip) and the associated academic journal article is here. See this thread on X for a summary.

Read the academic article to familiarize yourself with the basics of the water usage data. You don’t need to know how these water usage levels were estimated, so you can skip over those parts. We are going to focus on visualizing the water levels using the estimates that they generated.

1. Join data

First, let’s create a data set with all years/crops together in one data frame. Below is some code to help you get started. Add comments to each place there is ## to explain what the chunk of code is doing. Then add code to the Tranforming data Section to transform the data into a data frame with 5 columns: GEOID, crop, source, year, and value (indicating km^3 of water).

Note that eval = F at the start of the chunk will prevent this chunk from evaluating when you knit the document. You can temporarily remove it if you’d like, but you’ll want to add it back before knitting the document so that knitting takes less time.

sources = c('gwd', 'sw', 'gwa')
years = 2008:2020
d = NULL

for(s in sources){
  cat(s, '') ## show progress
  
  for(year in years){
    cat(year, '') ## show progress
  
    ## Read in data by combining 'rawdata/', source, '_', year, '.csv' into a filename
    filename = paste0('rawdata/', s, '_', year, '.csv')
    df = read.csv(filename)
    head(df)
    
    
    ## Tranform data #######################################
    ## Use `pivot_longer`, `separate`, and/or other functions to transform this
    ## data frame into a data frame with 5 columns: 
    ## GEOID, crop, source, year, and value (indicating km^3 of water)
    df = df %>% 
      pivot_longer(cols = -GEOID, names_to = "crop", values_to = "value") %>% 
      separate(col = crop, into = c("crop", "source", "year"), sep = "\\.")

    ## end of transforming data ############################
    
    ## Add this dataframe to `d`, which is a collection of all previous data frames
    d = rbind(d, df)
  }
  
  cat('\n') ## start a new line before showing progress for the next source
}
head(d)
tail(d)

2. Summaries of data

Find the mean, the change from 2008 to 2020, and the percent change from 2008 to 2020, for each crop and each source (SWW, GWW, GWD).

(dd1 <- d %>%
  group_by(crop, src, year) %>%
  summarise(value = sum(value)) %>%
  group_by(crop, src) %>%
  mutate(mean = mean(value)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = year, values_from = value) %>%
  mutate(change = `2020` - `2008`) %>%
  mutate(percent_change = (change/`2008`)*100) %>%
  select(crop, src, mean, change, percent_change))

## Bar chart of mean water usage by crop and source

(g1 <-  ggplot(dd1, aes(x = crop, y = mean, fill = src)) +

Two other options for visualizing a numeric variable broken down by two different categorical variable would be a tile plot/grid plot (e.g. https://github.com/bmacGTPM/pubtheme?tab=readme-ov-file#grid-plot) and a mosiac plot (https://haleyjeppson.github.io/ggmosaic/).

4. Create a tile plot/grid plot of the data in Figure 4.

## From pubtheme repo

title = "Water usage by crop and source (km^3)"
(g = ggplot(dd1, 
           aes(x    = crop, 
               y    = src, 
               fill = mean)) + ## hacky way to add a legend for NA values. See below
  geom_tile(linewidth   = 0.4, 
            show.legend = T, 
            color       = pubdarkgray) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low      = pubgradgray,
                      high     = pubblue, 
                      na.value = pubmediumgray, ## same color as below
                      oob      = squish, 
                      breaks   = c(0, 15, 40)) +
  
  ## hacky way to add a legend for NA values
    
  labs(title    = title,
       x    = 'Crop', 
       y    = 'Source', ## Optional
       fill = 'Mean water usage (km^3)') +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)))

6. What are the benefits (other than it fits on one plot) and drawbacks of these two plots?

In the tile plot, there is a value (other_sctg4, sw) that has a much higher value than the rest of the values. This causes some granularity to be lost when visualizing the rest of the values since they are close together and lumped into similar color bins. It is, however, easier to quickly see the difference between values.

The mosiac plot is able to show the granularity of the values better since it also represents the value with the bar widths. However, this does cause an issue when some bars are very narrow and the labels are too close together to read.

7. Figure 6

Figure 6 uses a different color scale for each plot. Discuss the benefits and drawbacks of this choice. What was the main purposes of this figure? Given the main purpose, would you recommend using the same color scale, or different color scales, for each plot?

The choice to use a different color scale for each plot is beneficial because the range of values for each crop-source combination is different. This makes it easier to contrast values for a single combination independent of the other combinations. A drawback of this choice is that each map is not necessarily comparable to other maps because the scale changes each time. The main purpose of this figure is to show the geographic distribution of mean water usage for each crop-source combination. Given this purpose, I would recommend using the same color scale because the maps are not meant to be compared to eachother, and this method seems appropriate for comparing values within a single map.

8. Figure 8

Figure 8 also uses a different color scale for each plot. Discuss the benefits and drawbacks of this choice. What was the main purposes of this figure? Given the main purpose, would you recommend using the same color scale, or different color scales, for each plot?

Using a different color scale for this figure may not be as advantageous as the previous example because the values are meant to be compared across time, as seen on the y-axis. However, it still serves the same purpose of comparing regional difference in value within each map.

The purpose of this figure was to show a geographic distribution of the change in water usage over a 5-year period for each source. Given this purpose, I would recommend using a different color scale so the maps can be compared across time.

10. Custom visualization

What is another question you have about this data? Create a visualization that attempt to answer your question.

I am curious about the distribution of water usage by crop and source and I want to visually compare the values going from each crop and going from each source. I’ve created a chord diagram to visualize this.

## Chord diagram of water usage by crop and source
dd2 <- dd1 %>% select(crop, src, mean)
colnames(dd2) <- c("x", "y", "z")

colors <- c("#D9C57C", "#C7B299", "#A8C4C4", "#C4BAA1", "#B3C7B3", "#D9B08C", "#B4B4A0", "#CC9999", "#C4D0C0", "#B6A9A9", "#9ECA83", "#BCB5A1", "#DAC3A1", "#B0B0B0", "#E2D3C3", "#C0C0C0", "#E2D5B2", "#B0C0C0", "#D1CBB9", "#A3A3A3", "#4682B4", "#4169E1", "#1E90FF")

circos.clear()
circos.par(
  canvas.xlim = c(-0.25, 0.25),
  canvas.ylim = c(-1.1, 1.5),
  start.degree = 270, 
  gap.degree = 2
)
chordDiagram(dd2, transparency = .1, grid.col = colors, annotationTrack = "grid", 
    preAllocateTracks = list(track.height = max(strwidth(unlist(dimnames(dd2))))))
circos.track(track.index = 1, panel.fun = function(x, y) {
    circos.text(CELL_META$xcenter, CELL_META$ylim[1], CELL_META$sector.index, 
        facing = "clockwise", niceFacing = TRUE, adj = c(0, 0.5), cex = 0.9)
}, bg.border = NA)
mtext("Mean water usage by crop and source", side = 3, cex = 1.2)
